\hypertarget{abstract}{%
\subsection{Abstract}\label{abstract}}

We propose \textbf{Gravitational Structural Collapse (GSC)} as a
renormalized, scale-covariant framework in which the standard
interpretation of cosmological redshift as \emph{metric expansion} is
replaced by a physically equivalent description: a \textbf{freeze-frame
(conformally static) background spacetime} with a \textbf{time-evolving
matter scale}. In this formulation, the observed growth of cosmological
distances in atomic units is attributed to the \textbf{continuous
shrinkage of bound matter} (equivalently, the growth of particle masses
in a freeze-frame description), while \textbf{dimensionless local
physics remains invariant}.

The core dynamical hypothesis of v10 is that the collapse of the
characteristic matter scale is driven by \textbf{renormalization-group
(RG) running of gravity}: the effective Newton coupling becomes strongly
enhanced as the system approaches a critical ultraviolet scale. We
replace all prior large-extra-dimension (ADD/LED) toy enhancements with
a single RG-flow mechanism featuring a \textbf{sharp, pole-like
crossover (Pad\'e-type) enhancement} in the coupling. This provides a
natural route to an
effective phantom equation of state (\(w_{\rm eff} < -1\)) without
introducing ad hoc fluid components.

A key conceptual addition is \textbf{energy bookkeeping}. In standard
FLRW cosmology, global energy is not generally a Noether charge because
a time-dependent background lacks a global timelike Killing symmetry. In
the GSC freeze frame, a global time-translation symmetry is restored and
total energy can be defined as a conserved Noether quantity, while the
apparent ``photon energy loss'' of redshift is reinterpreted as the
evolution of the detector scale.

GSC v10 is deliberately minimal: it makes one \textbf{decisive
discriminating prediction} beyond the LambdaCDM concordance model,
namely the \textbf{sign of the redshift drift} (\(dz/dt_0\)) at high
redshift. For the toy late-time histories considered here (monotonic
accelerated collapse satisfying \(H(z)<H_0(1+z)\) in the quasar range),
these histories imply \(\dot z>0\) at \(z\sim 2\)--5, in contrast with
the standard expectation \(\dot z<0\) in that range. This prediction is
testable with upcoming ultra-stable
high-resolution spectroscopy (ELT/ANDES; precursor programs with
VLT/ESPRESSO).
Because Sandage--Loeb is a kinematic relation, this is explicitly a
\textbf{history-vs-history} test (\(H(z)_{\rm GSC}\) versus
\(H(z)_{\Lambda\mathrm{CDM}}\)), not a frame-label test.

\begin{center}\rule{0.5\linewidth}{0.5pt}\end{center}

