\hypertarget{motivation-and-design-principles}{%
\section{1. Motivation and Design
Principles}\label{motivation-and-design-principles}}

\hypertarget{the-empirical-starting-point-cosmological-redshift}{%
\subsubsection{1.1 The empirical starting point: cosmological
redshift}\label{the-empirical-starting-point-cosmological-redshift}}

The observable fact is the systematic redshift of distant spectral
lines. The standard interpretation is that spacetime expands (FLRW
metric), stretching photon wavelengths.

\hypertarget{relationship-to-wetterich-2013-and-key-differentiation}{%
\subsubsection{1.2 Relationship to Wetterich (2013) and key
differentiation}\label{relationship-to-wetterich-2013-and-key-differentiation}}

The conformal-frame reinterpretation of cosmological redshift as arising
from evolving matter scales rather than metric expansion was emphasized
by Wetterich (2013) in the scalar-tensor / variable-gravity literature.
Via a \textbf{conformal field redefinition}, an expanding FLRW
description can be mapped to a frame with approximately static
background geometry and time-evolving particle masses and rulers. As
stressed in that literature, this is a field redefinition: it does not,
by itself, constitute new physics.

Frameworks of this type are therefore often perceived as observationally
equivalent to LambdaCDM unless one commits to additional dynamical
structure that fixes the cosmological history \(H(z)\). In GSC v10 we
make two minimal commitments:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Mechanism framing (phenomenological):} the evolution of the
  universal scale \(\sigma(t)\) is driven by RG-motivated, scale-dependent
  gravity. In v10 this is an explicit parameterization (not a
  first-principles derivation).
\item
  \textbf{Testability upgrade:} we emphasize a look-back observable
  (redshift drift) that constrains the selected late-time history once a
  specific \(H(z)\) is specified. The key discriminator is the
  \emph{sign} of \(\dot z\) in the quasar range, testable with upcoming
  ultra-stable spectroscopy (ELT/ANDES; precursors with VLT/ESPRESSO).
\end{itemize}

\begin{center}
\setlength{\tabcolsep}{4pt}
\renewcommand{\arraystretch}{1.15}
\begin{tabular}{@{}p{0.30\linewidth} p{0.28\linewidth} p{0.35\linewidth}@{}}
\toprule
Model & High-\(z\) drift sign (\(z \gtrsim 2\)) & Comment \\
\midrule
LambdaCDM & \(\dot z < 0\) & past deceleration (matter domination) \\
GSC (monotonic accelerated collapse) & \(\dot z > 0\) & accelerated collapse toward today \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\hypertarget{the-guiding-design-principles-of-v10}{%
\subsubsection{1.3 The guiding design principles of
v10}\label{the-guiding-design-principles-of-v10}}

v10 enforces four principles that v9.1 violated in places:

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
\item
  \textbf{One gravity mechanism.}\\
  No ADD/LED exponents, no curve-fitted power laws. The only allowed
  mechanism for ``strong gravity'' is RG flow.
\item
  \textbf{Universality over cleverness.}\\
  Local null results (GPS, atomic clocks, equivalence principle) are not
  ``marginal survivals''; they are required consequences of
  universal/coherent scaling.
\item
  \textbf{No fragile anomaly-collecting.}\\
  v10 does not claim to ``solve'' neutron lifetime, Casimir deviations,
  Li-7, etc. unless the mechanism survives a clean scale analysis.
\item
  \textbf{Falsifiability first.}\\
  v10 has one primary discriminant: the sign of redshift drift at high
	  redshift.
\end{enumerate}

\hypertarget{historical-context-and-failure-modes}{%
\subsubsection{1.4 Historical context and failure modes (Dirac, tired
light, conformal
cosmologies)}\label{historical-context-and-failure-modes}}

The idea that a change of ``fundamental'' scales could mimic expansion
has a long history. Dirac's varying-\(G\) proposal (1937) is an
instructive precedent: it was testable and ultimately constrained,
highlighting the need to keep claims tightly tied to clean observables.

Separately, ``tired light'' mechanisms (photon energy-loss or scattering
processes) are ruled out by classic expansion tests, including the Tolman
surface-brightness relation and the observed \((1+z)\) time dilation of
Type Ia supernova light curves (as well as the near-perfect blackbody
spectrum of the CMB). \textbf{GSC is not a tired-light mechanism}: it
preserves time dilation and Tolman dimming within the conformal,
scale-covariant measurement model (Sec.~3.4), assuming standard photon
number conservation along null geodesics rather than ad hoc energy-loss
physics.

In this context, Wetterich-style conformal descriptions are best viewed
as alternative variable choices; here we emphasize a look-back observable
(redshift drift) that breaks the perceived equivalence once one commits
to a specific late-time \(H(z)\) history.

\begin{center}\rule{0.5\linewidth}{0.5pt}\end{center}

\hypertarget{the-core-postulates-of-gsc-v10}{%
\section{2. The Core Postulates of GSC
v10}\label{the-core-postulates-of-gsc-v10}}

We define the theory by a small set of postulates (the ``axioms'' of the
framework). Everything else is derived or deferred.

\hypertarget{postulate-p1-static-background-in-the-freeze-frame}{%
\subsection{Postulate P1: Static background in the freeze
frame}\label{postulate-p1-static-background-in-the-freeze-frame}}

There exists a conformal frame (the \textbf{freeze frame}) in which the
cosmological background metric is approximately Minkowski,

\[
\bar g_{\mu\nu} \simeq \eta_{\mu\nu},
\]

up to small perturbations describing local gravitational fields. There
is no global expansion of spatial geometry in this frame.

\hypertarget{postulate-p2-a-universal-scale-field-controls-all-matter-scales}{%
\subsection{Postulate P2: A universal scale field controls all matter
scales}\label{postulate-p2-a-universal-scale-field-controls-all-matter-scales}}

There exists a homogeneous scalar scale field \(\sigma(t)\) such that
the characteristic size of bound matter (atomic and hadronic) is
proportional to \(\sigma\),

\[
\ell_{\rm bound}(t) \propto \sigma(t),
\]

so that \textbf{matter shrinks} as \(\sigma(t)\) decreases.
Equivalently, particle masses increase as

\[
m_i(t) \propto \sigma(t)^{-1}.
\]

In v10 we adopt \textbf{universal scaling}: all SM mass scales (QCD
confinement, Higgs vev, lepton masses, nuclear scales) co-scale in such
a way that \textbf{dimensionless couplings and ratios} remain constant
to high precision.

To preserve the constancy of \emph{dimensionless} gravitational
couplings (e.g.~\(\alpha_G \equiv G m_p^2/(\hbar c)\)), the framework
further requires that the effective Planck mass co-scales with the
matter scale,

\[
M_{\rm Pl}(t) \propto \sigma(t)^{-1},
\]

so that the infrared (macroscopic) Newton coupling scales as

\[
G_{\rm IR}(t) \propto \sigma(t)^2.
\]

This scaling is \emph{frame dependent}: in an Einstein frame with
constant \(M_{\rm Pl}\) the same physics is described by an expanding
metric; in the freeze frame the background metric is static while masses
and \(G\) evolve coherently.

\hypertarget{postulate-p3-gravity-is-renormalized-and-scale-dependent-rg-flow}{%
\subsection{Postulate P3: Gravity is renormalized and scale-dependent
(RG
flow)}\label{postulate-p3-gravity-is-renormalized-and-scale-dependent-rg-flow}}

The effective Newton coupling runs with physical scale \(k\) (or length
\(\ell \sim 1/k\)). In the ultraviolet it exhibits a rapid enhancement
consistent with the idea of asymptotic safety / nonperturbative RG flow.

For the purposes of v10, we encode the essential behavior in a minimal
\emph{pole-like Pad\'e / sharp-crossover parameterization},

\[
G(k) \;=\; \frac{G_{\rm IR}}{1 - \left(\frac{k}{k_*}\right)^2},
\qquad
k_* \;\text{(phenomenological UV scale)},
\]

Motivation note: earlier iterations heuristically associated \(k_*\)
with a hadronic/confinement scale, but in v11.0.0 it is treated
phenomenologically.

This is an \emph{effective} parametrization of a rapid crossover in
\(G(k)\); we do \emph{not} claim a physical divergence at \(k=k_*\). In a
UV-complete treatment one expects regulated behavior (fixed points,
crossover/walking, or other nonperturbative completion).

or equivalently in length language,

\[
G(\ell) \;=\; \frac{G_{\rm IR}}{1 - \left(\frac{\ell_*}{\ell}\right)^2},
\qquad
\ell_* = k_*^{-1}.
\]

\textbf{Interpretation:} as the relevant physical scale approaches a
critical ultraviolet scale \(\ell \rightarrow \ell_*\), the effective
coupling grows sharply. This removes any need for large arbitrary
exponents (e.g., \(n \approx 36\)).

\textbf{Important:} In v10, \(\ell_*\) (or \(k_*\)) is treated as a
\emph{phenomenological UV scale}, heuristically associated with hadronic
physics, but not assumed as a derived identity. Deriving it from first
principles is an open problem and is explicitly listed in the roadmap.

\hypertarget{postulate-p4-observables-are-dimensionless-local-drift-is-a-null-prediction}{%
\subsection{Postulate P4: Observables are dimensionless; local drift is
a null
prediction}\label{postulate-p4-observables-are-dimensionless-local-drift-is-a-null-prediction}}

Any local experiment compares dimensionless ratios (clock ratios,
frequency ratios, orbital-to-atomic times, etc.). Under universal
scaling, these ratios remain constant. Therefore:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Local comparisons (GPS, metrology, clock networks) must show
  null secular drift} beyond standard GR/SM predictions.
\item
  Only \textbf{look-back} observables (those comparing emission
  vs.~observation epochs) can reveal the evolution of \(\sigma(t)\).
\end{itemize}

\begin{center}\rule{0.5\linewidth}{0.5pt}\end{center}

\hypertarget{conformal-frame-map-expansion-vs.-shrinking-matter}{%
\section{3. Conformal Frame Map: Expansion vs.~Shrinking
Matter}\label{conformal-frame-map-expansion-vs.-shrinking-matter}}

This section is the ``mathematical shield'': it shows how the
static-space description is connected to the usual expanding-space
description.

\hypertarget{frame-map}{%
\subsection{3.1 Frame map}\label{frame-map}}

Let \(g_{\mu\nu}\) denote the metric in the usual Einstein-frame
cosmological description (expanding FLRW), and let \(\bar g_{\mu\nu}\)
denote the freeze-frame metric.

We define a conformal transformation

\[
g_{\mu\nu} \;=\; \Omega^2(\sigma)\, \bar g_{\mu\nu},
\qquad
\Omega(\sigma) \equiv \frac{\sigma_0}{\sigma(t)}.
\]

Then the Einstein-frame scale factor is

\[
a(t) \;=\; \Omega(\sigma(t)) \;=\; \frac{\sigma_0}{\sigma(t)}.
\]

Thus, expansion (\(a\) increasing) is equivalent to collapse (\(\sigma\)
decreasing).

\hypertarget{redshift-in-the-freeze-frame}{%
\subsection{3.2 Redshift in the freeze
frame}\label{redshift-in-the-freeze-frame}}

For an emitter at time \(t_e\) and observer at \(t_0\),

\[
1+z \;=\; \frac{a(t_0)}{a(t_e)} \;=\; \frac{\sigma(t_e)}{\sigma(t_0)}.
\]

This means that the observed redshift can be interpreted as the ratio of
matter scales between emission and observation: spectral lines emitted
when atoms were larger (smaller masses) are redshifted relative to
today's atoms.

\hypertarget{what-is-and-is-not-claimed}{%
\subsection{3.3 What is (and is not)
claimed}\label{what-is-and-is-not-claimed}}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  The existence of the frame map is not controversial: it follows from
  scalar-tensor field redefinitions.
\item
  GSC's physical claim is that there exists a \textbf{dynamical reason}
  for \(\sigma(t)\) to evolve, and that the freeze frame is the natural
  bookkeeping frame for conserved quantities.
\end{itemize}

This equivalence point is double-edged: if two descriptions use the same
physical history \(H(z)\), they predict the same dimensionless
observables. Therefore the empirical target is not ``frame label versus
frame label'' but the specific dynamics that selects a non-LambdaCDM
history. In this submission, falsifiability is tied to that selected
history class.

\hypertarget{classic-expansion-tests-retained}{%
\subsection{3.4 Classic expansion tests retained (time dilation, Tolman
dimming)}\label{classic-expansion-tests-retained}}

Because the GSC interpretation is implemented as a conformal
measurement-model map (not as photon energy-loss physics), it preserves
the classic expansion tests that rule out tired-light analogies.

\textbf{SN Ia time dilation.} From
\[
1+z = \frac{\sigma(t_e)}{\sigma(t_0)},
\]
and the scaling of characteristic atomic times
\(\tau_{\rm atom}(t)\propto 1/m(t)\propto \sigma(t)\), a process with a
local characteristic duration \(\Delta t\propto \tau_{\rm atom}\) obeys
\[
\frac{\Delta t_{\rm obs}}{\Delta t_{\rm em}}
= \frac{\tau_{\rm atom}(t_e)}{\tau_{\rm atom}(t_0)}
= \frac{\sigma(t_e)}{\sigma(t_0)}
= 1+z,
\]
matching the observed \((1+z)\) stretch of SN light curves.

\textbf{Tolman surface brightness.} With photon number conservation along
null geodesics,
\[
F=\frac{L}{4\pi D_L^2},
\qquad
D_L=(1+z)^2D_A,
\]
and therefore for an object with physical area \(A\) and angular size
\(\theta^2\sim A/D_A^2\),
\[
SB \equiv \frac{F}{\theta^2} \propto \frac{L/A}{(1+z)^4}.
\]
In GSC this standard \((1+z)^{-4}\) Tolman dimming is retained via the
conformal map and Etherington reciprocity, so the framework is not a
tired-light mechanism.

\begin{center}\rule{0.5\linewidth}{0.5pt}\end{center}

\hypertarget{renormalized-scale-dependent-gravity-rg-flow-landau-pole}{%
\section{4. Renormalized Scale-Dependent Gravity (RG Flow, Pole-like
Crossover)}\label{renormalized-scale-dependent-gravity-rg-flow-landau-pole}}

\hypertarget{connection-to-asymptotic-safety-conceptual}{%
\subsection{4.1 Connection to asymptotic safety
(conceptual)}\label{connection-to-asymptotic-safety-conceptual}}

The asymptotic safety program posits that quantum gravity may be
nonperturbatively renormalizable, with couplings approaching a UV fixed
point. In many functional RG treatments, the dimensionless Newton
coupling \(g(k)=k^2 G(k)\) approaches a nontrivial fixed point, implying
non-classical running of \(G(k)\).

v10 does \textbf{not} attempt a full FRG derivation. Instead it uses the
robust qualitative lesson: \textbf{gravity need not be a constant
coupling across scales}, and strong enhancement can occur in the UV.

\hypertarget{minimal-parametrization-used-in-v10}{%
\subsection{4.2 Minimal parametrization used in
v10}\label{minimal-parametrization-used-in-v10}}

We adopt:

\[
G(k) = \frac{G_{\rm IR}}{1-(k/k_*)^2}.
\]

This form has three useful properties:

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Correct IR limit:} \(G(k)\rightarrow G_{\rm IR}\) for
  \(k\ll k_*\).
\item
  \textbf{Rapid UV enhancement:} \(G\) grows quickly as
  \(k\rightarrow k_*\).
\item
  \textbf{No arbitrary exponents:} unlike ADD-style power laws.
\end{enumerate}

We emphasize again: this is a minimal \emph{pole-like crossover}
parametrization capturing qualitative RG behavior. We do \emph{not} claim
a physical divergence at \(k=k_*\); in a UV-complete picture one expects
regulated behavior (fixed points / crossover / walking). The scale
\(k_*\) is treated phenomenologically in v10. The detailed FRG beta
functions are deferred to a technical companion note.

\hypertarget{why-this-matters-for-cosmology-in-gsc}{%
\subsection{4.3 Why this matters for cosmology in
GSC}\label{why-this-matters-for-cosmology-in-gsc}}

Because the matter scale \(\sigma(t)\) controls the characteristic
physical scales inside bound systems, the RG-enhanced gravity can couple
back into the evolution of \(\sigma(t)\). As \(\sigma(t)\) decreases,
the relevant internal scales probe higher \(k\), and the effective
coupling increases --- producing \textbf{accelerated structural
collapse}. In v11.0.0, the identification between RG scale and
cosmological/structural scale (e.g.~\(k \leftrightarrow 1/\sigma\)) is
treated as a working ansatz, not a FRG derivation, and remains an
explicit open-problem item.

\textbf{RG scale identification note (\(k(\sigma)\)):} throughout the
current release, the map from FRG scale \(k\) to the bound-matter
evolution variable \(\sigma\) is a phenomenological identification used
for modeling consistency, not a first-principles derivation from
asymptotic safety. See
\texttt{v11.0.0/docs/rg\_scale\_identification.md} for the precise claim
boundary and deferred derivation scope.

This is the v10 replacement for the v8--v9 ADD-based ``\(n=36\)''
mechanism.

\begin{center}\rule{0.5\linewidth}{0.5pt}\end{center}

\hypertarget{scale-covariance-and-why-local-metrology-sees-no-drift}{%
\section{5. Scale Covariance and Why Local Metrology Sees No
Drift}\label{scale-covariance-and-why-local-metrology-sees-no-drift}}

The critiques of v9.1 emphasized GPS, atomic clocks, Oklo, pulsars, and
equivalence-principle tests. v10 does not treat these as external
``threats''; they are internal consistency requirements.

\hypertarget{scale-covariance-lemma-informal-statement}{%
\subsection{5.1 Scale-covariance lemma (informal
statement)}\label{scale-covariance-lemma-informal-statement}}

If all dimensionful quantities in the local experiment (masses, lengths,
gravitational parameters, and the clock transitions themselves) co-scale
with a single \(\sigma(t)\), then any dimensionless ratio measured by
that experiment is invariant.

This is the central reason that \textbf{local physics is blind} to the
global evolution of \(\sigma(t)\).

\hypertarget{example-atomic-clocks-vs-orbital-dynamics-gps-logic}{%
\subsection{5.2 Example: atomic clocks vs orbital dynamics (GPS
logic)}\label{example-atomic-clocks-vs-orbital-dynamics-gps-logic}}

Atomic transition frequencies scale (schematically) as

\[
\nu_{\rm atom} \propto m_e\, \alpha^2,
\]

while orbital frequencies scale as

\[
\nu_{\rm orb} \sim \sqrt{\frac{GM}{r^3}}.
\]

Under universal scaling, \(m_e\propto \sigma^{-1}\) and the size of
bound systems (including orbit sizes expressed in local rods) scales as
\(r\propto \sigma\). Macroscopic masses scale as
\(M\propto \sigma^{-1}\). With the freeze-frame infrared scaling
\(G_{\rm IR}\propto \sigma^2\) (Postulate P2), the gravitational
parameter obeys

\[
GM \propto \sigma^2\,\sigma^{-1} = \sigma.
\]

Therefore

\[
\nu_{\rm orb} \sim \sqrt{\frac{GM}{r^3}} \propto \sqrt{\frac{\sigma}{\sigma^3}} = \sigma^{-1}.
\]

Both the orbital frequency and the atomic transition frequency scale as
\(\sigma^{-1}\), so the ratio \(\nu_{\rm atom}/\nu_{\rm orb}\) is
invariant.

\textbf{v10 stance:} the observed long-term success of GPS is therefore
not a problem to ``survive''; it is a \emph{null prediction} of coherent
scaling.

\hypertarget{wep-and-universality}{%
\subsection{5.3 WEP and universality}\label{wep-and-universality}}

Any non-universal scaling (e.g., the QCD sector scaling differently from
the electroweak sector) would generate composition-dependent
accelerations, which are tightly constrained by Weak Equivalence
Principle (WEP) tests.

In particular, the MICROSCOPE mission reports a null result at the level
of \(\eta \sim 10^{-15}\) for composition pairs such as Ti vs Pt (Eotvos
parameter; see the cited experimental literature).

Therefore v10 elevates universality from an ``assumption'' to a
\textbf{required symmetry}: the framework must be constructed so that
all sectors scale coherently at the level demanded by modern WEP bounds.

\hypertarget{si-20192018-and-operational-definitions}{%
\subsection{5.4 SI-2019/2018 and operational
definitions}\label{si-20192018-and-operational-definitions}}

Modern SI definitions fix numerical values of \(h\), \(c\), and the Cs
hyperfine frequency. This emphasizes a key point aligned with v10:
\textbf{units are operationally defined by specific physical systems},
and only dimensionless comparisons are fundamental.

v10 interprets SI stability as consistent with coherent scaling: if all
local clocks and rods are governed by the same evolving scale, the SI
realizations remain self-consistent and show no internal drift.

\hypertarget{oklo-long-baseline-bounds-and-what-v10-must-satisfy}{%
\subsection{5.5 Oklo, long-baseline bounds, and what v10 must
satisfy}\label{oklo-long-baseline-bounds-and-what-v10-must-satisfy}}

Long-baseline constraints (geophysical and astrophysical) are often
summarized as bounds on the time variation of dimensionless quantities
such as the fine-structure constant \(\alpha\) or mass ratios. A
canonical example is the Oklo natural fission reactor, where isotope
data constrain possible shifts in nuclear resonance energies over
\({\sim}10^9\) year timescales.

In v10, the \emph{target design} is that \textbf{dimensionless couplings
and ratios are constant} under the universal scaling postulate. In that
ideal limit, Oklo-type bounds are automatically satisfied because only
dimensionless combinations (e.g.~resonance energy relative to the
relevant nuclear scale) enter the physics.

\hypertarget{however-critics-are-correct-that-this-is-not-something-to-hand-wave-oklo-constrains-not-only-the-location-of-a-resonance-but-also-aspects-of-widths-and-reaction-rates-that-can-mix-different-contributions.-v10-therefore-treats-oklo-and-similar-systems-such-as-pulsar-timing-bounds-on-dot-gg-as-mandatory-consistency-checks-for-any-non-universal-corrections-to-the-scaling-symmetry.}{%
\subsection{\texorpdfstring{However, critics are correct that this is
not something to hand-wave: Oklo constrains not only the location of a
resonance but also aspects of widths and reaction rates that can mix
different contributions. v10 therefore treats Oklo (and similar systems
such as pulsar timing bounds on \(\dot G/G\)) as \emph{mandatory
consistency checks} for any non-universal corrections to the scaling
symmetry.}{However, critics are correct that this is not something to hand-wave: Oklo constrains not only the location of a resonance but also aspects of widths and reaction rates that can mix different contributions. v10 therefore treats Oklo (and similar systems such as pulsar timing bounds on \textbackslash dot G/G) as mandatory consistency checks for any non-universal corrections to the scaling symmetry.}}\label{however-critics-are-correct-that-this-is-not-something-to-hand-wave-oklo-constrains-not-only-the-location-of-a-resonance-but-also-aspects-of-widths-and-reaction-rates-that-can-mix-different-contributions.-v10-therefore-treats-oklo-and-similar-systems-such-as-pulsar-timing-bounds-on-dot-gg-as-mandatory-consistency-checks-for-any-non-universal-corrections-to-the-scaling-symmetry.}}

\hypertarget{parameterized-departures-from-universality-risk-model}{%
\subsection{5.6 Parameterized departures from universality (risk
model)}\label{parameterized-departures-from-universality-risk-model}}

To make the role of universality explicit, it is useful to parameterize
small departures as a \emph{risk model}. A minimal two-parameter encoding
of ``non-universality'' is to allow small differential scalings between
an electromagnetic/leptonic scale and a hadronic/nuclear scale, e.g.

\[
m_e \propto \sigma^{-1-\epsilon_{\rm EM}},
\qquad
m_p\;(\text{or }\Lambda_{\rm had}) \propto \sigma^{-1-\epsilon_{\rm QCD}}.
\]

Then \(\mu\equiv m_p/m_e\) drifts as

\[
\frac{d\ln\mu}{dt} = (\epsilon_{\rm EM}-\epsilon_{\rm QCD})\,H_\sigma,
\qquad
H_\sigma \equiv -\frac{\dot\sigma}{\sigma}.
\]

For a clock-ratio comparison \(A/B\), a generic drift template is

\[
\frac{d}{dt}\ln\left(\frac{\nu_A}{\nu_B}\right)
= K_\alpha^{AB}\frac{d\ln\alpha}{dt} + K_\mu^{AB}\frac{d\ln\mu}{dt} + \cdots,
\]

where the \(K\)'s are dimensionless sensitivity coefficients and
\(H_\sigma\equiv -\dot\sigma/\sigma\). At the present epoch
\(H_\sigma(t_0)=H_0\approx 7\times 10^{-11}\,{\rm yr^{-1}}\) (for
\(H_0\simeq 70\,{\rm km\,s^{-1}\,Mpc^{-1}}\)), so even
\(|\epsilon_{\rm EM}-\epsilon_{\rm QCD}|\sim 10^{-7}\) corresponds to an
order \({\sim}10^{-17}\,{\rm yr^{-1}}\) drift in \(\ln\mu\) \emph{before}
\(K\)-factors.

\textbf{v11.0.0 policy:} we set
\(\epsilon_{\rm EM}=\epsilon_{\rm QCD}=0\) (strict universality) in the
\emph{core claims}. Nonzero \(\epsilon\)'s are an explicit
parameterization of a failure mode that must be bounded by atomic-clock,
Oklo, and WEP constraints in any future non-universal extension; they
are not used in the late-time fits. See
\texttt{v11.0.0/docs/precision\_constraints\_translator.md}.

\hypertarget{global-energy-bookkeeping-and-noether-charge}{%
\section{6. Global Energy Bookkeeping and Noether
Charge}\label{global-energy-bookkeeping-and-noether-charge}}

\hypertarget{the-core-issue}{%
\subsection{6.1 The core issue}\label{the-core-issue}}

In a time-dependent cosmological spacetime, there is generally no global
timelike Killing vector, and therefore no globally conserved energy
associated with time translation symmetry. This is why the ``where does
photon energy go?'' question in an expanding universe does not admit a
simple global answer.

This is not a logical inconsistency of GR; it is a statement about the
symmetry structure of the background.

\hypertarget{the-gsc-claim}{%
\subsection{6.2 The GSC claim}\label{the-gsc-claim}}

In the freeze frame, the background is static (approximately Minkowski).
Therefore it possesses a time-translation symmetry and admits a global
Noether energy (up to boundary conditions and perturbations). In that
frame:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  photon energies are conserved along null propagation in the static
  background;
\item
  the apparent redshift is produced by the evolution of the
  detector/emitter energy scales.
\end{itemize}

This reframes the cosmological ``energy nonconservation'' intuition into
a symmetry-respecting accounting identity.

\hypertarget{why-this-is-a-selling-point-without-overclaiming}{%
\subsection{6.3 Why this is a selling point (without
overclaiming)}\label{why-this-is-a-selling-point-without-overclaiming}}

v10 does \textbf{not} claim that LambdaCDM is ``wrong because it
violates energy conservation.'' The correct statement is:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  in standard expanding backgrounds, the concept of a single global
  conserved energy is not generally defined;
\item
  GSC offers an alternative formulation in which a global energy can be
  defined and conserved.
\end{itemize}

\begin{center}\rule{0.5\linewidth}{0.5pt}\end{center}

\hypertarget{cosmological-dynamics-and-effective-equation-of-state}{%
\section{7. Cosmological Dynamics and Effective Equation of
State}\label{cosmological-dynamics-and-effective-equation-of-state}}

We define the collapse rate

\[
H_\sigma(t) \equiv -\frac{\dot{\sigma}}{\sigma},
\]

which maps to the usual Hubble parameter in the expanding frame:

\[
H(t) = \frac{\dot a}{a} = H_\sigma(t).
\]

If \(H_\sigma(t)\) increases with time (accelerating collapse), then the
effective equation of state satisfies

\[
w_{\rm eff} < -1
\quad \Longleftrightarrow \quad
\dot H > 0.
\]

In v10 we do not attempt to fit all background data. The focus is:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  identify the dynamical sign of \(\dot H\) implied by RG-driven
  collapse near a critical scale;
\item
  connect it to the redshift drift discriminant.
\end{itemize}

\begin{center}\rule{0.5\linewidth}{0.5pt}\end{center}

\hypertarget{the-golden-test-redshift-drift}{%
\section{8. The Golden Test: Redshift
Drift}\label{the-golden-test-redshift-drift}}

\hypertarget{definition}{%
\subsection{8.1 Definition}\label{definition}}

Redshift drift is the secular change of the observed redshift of a
distant source as measured over a human timescale:

\[
\dot z \equiv \frac{dz}{dt_0}.
\]

For any FLRW description, the Sandage--Loeb relation is

\[
\dot z = H_0(1+z) - H(z)
\quad\Rightarrow\quad
\dot z > 0 \;\Longleftrightarrow\; H(z) < H_0(1+z),
\]
and ``positive drift throughout the quasar range'' requires this
inequality for all \(z\in[2,5]\).

This relation is kinematic. It does not discriminate conformal frames by
itself; it discriminates competing histories \(H(z)\) once they are
specified.
If two models share the same \(H(z)\), this observable cannot select a
preferred frame label at this level.

It is also useful to define the corresponding velocity drift rate,
\[
\dot v \equiv c\,\frac{\dot z}{1+z}
= c\left[H_0 - \frac{H(z)}{1+z}\right].
\]

This is an observable independent of distance ladder calibrations.

\hypertarget{standard-expectation-lambdacdm}{%
\subsection{8.2 Standard expectation
(LambdaCDM)}\label{standard-expectation-lambdacdm}}

In LambdaCDM, the universe decelerates at high redshift (matter
domination), so \(H(z)\) grows rapidly with \(z\). As a consequence,
\(\dot z\) changes sign and becomes negative at sufficiently high
redshift (typically in the quasar range \(z\sim 2\)--5).

\hypertarget{gsc-v10-prediction-positive-drift-at-all-redshifts}{%
\subsection{8.3 GSC v10: drift-sign criterion and toy
histories}\label{gsc-v10-prediction-positive-drift-at-all-redshifts}}

In GSC v10, the collapse is driven by RG-enhanced gravity and is assumed
to be \textbf{accelerating} in the sense that \(H_\sigma(t)\) increases
with cosmic time. Equivalently, \(H(z)\) decreases toward the past more
slowly than the \((1+z)\) factor.

A simple representative parameterization is a toy power-law history,

\[
H(z) = H_0 (1+z)^p,
\qquad 0<p<1,
\]

\emph{Simulation note:} In the accompanying v10.1 toy simulations, we
adopt a representative choice \(p=0.5\) solely for visualization. The
\textbf{sign} result \(\dot z>0\) is robust for any \(0<p<1\), and the
detailed form of \(p(z)\) is explicitly left to a Phase-2 derivation
from the RG dynamics.

This yields

\[
\dot z = H_0\left[(1+z) - (1+z)^p\right].
\]

Since \((1+z)^p < (1+z)\) for \(z>0\) when \(0<p<1\), this class
satisfies the positivity criterion \(H(z)<H_0(1+z)\) and therefore gives
\(\dot z>0\). Transition histories that asymptotically satisfy
\(H(z)<H_0(1+z)\) for \(z\gtrsim 2\) likewise yield \(\dot z>0\) in the
quasar range.

\textbf{Therefore:}

\begin{quote}
\textbf{Prediction (P-redshift-drift):} For quasars in the range
\(2\lesssim z \lesssim 5\), the late-time GSC toy histories used here
imply \(\dot z > 0\), whereas standard LambdaCDM implies \(\dot z < 0\).
\end{quote}

This is the primary falsifier of the framework.

\hypertarget{experimental-prospects}{%
\subsection{8.4 Experimental prospects}\label{experimental-prospects}}

Redshift drift is often expressed as an apparent spectroscopic velocity
drift

\[
\Delta v \equiv c\,\frac{\Delta z}{1+z},
\]

which is expected to be of order \({\rm cm\,s^{-1}}\) over decade
baselines for \(z\sim 2\)--5 targets.

\emph{Illustrative amplitude (not a fit prediction):} for the toy
parameterization \(H(z)=H_0(1+z)^p\),
\[
\dot v = c\,H_0\left[1-(1+z)^{p-1}\right].
\]
Table~\ref{tab:dv-illustrative-andes} gives illustrative \(\Delta v\)
values over \(\Delta t=20\) years for representative ANDES redshift bins,
comparing a Planck-like LambdaCDM benchmark (\(H_0=67.4\),
\(\Omega_m=0.315\)) to a toy GSC power-law history with \(p=0.9\) (same
\(H_0\)). These values are \emph{illustrative} (not fit predictions); the
\emph{sign} at high \(z\) is the core discriminator.

\begin{table}[htbp]
\centering
\small
\setlength{\tabcolsep}{4pt}
\renewcommand{\arraystretch}{1.15}
\begin{tabular}{@{}lrrrrr@{}}
\textbf{Model (illustrative)} & \textbf{\(z=2.0\)} & \textbf{\(2.5\)} & \textbf{\(3.0\)} & \textbf{\(3.5\)} & \textbf{\(4.5\)} \\
\hline
LambdaCDM (Planck-like) & \(-0.43\) & \(-3.15\) & \(-5.84\) & \(-8.46\) & \(-13.42\) \\
GSC toy power-law (\(p=0.9\)) & \(+4.30\) & \(+4.87\) & \(+5.35\) & \(+5.77\) & \(+6.48\) \\
\end{tabular}
\caption{Illustrative velocity drift \(\Delta v\) in \({\rm cm\,s^{-1}}\)
over \(\Delta t=20\) years for representative ANDES redshift bins. This
is a toy illustration (not a fit prediction); the sign in the quasar
range is the core discriminator.}
\label{tab:dv-illustrative-andes}
\end{table}

Upcoming ultra-stable, high-resolution spectroscopy on extremely large
telescopes is explicitly designed to reach this regime. The ELT/ANDES
science case lists the \emph{Sandage test} (redshift drift) as a top
priority and targets long-term stability at the
\({\sim}1\,\mathrm{cm\,s^{-1}}\) level.

Recent feasibility analyses using VLT/ESPRESSO data illustrate both the
difficulty and the realism of the measurement: the observed drift over a
5-year baseline is consistent with zero, while end-to-end forecasts show
that a definitive detection in the standard scenario requires very large
integration times distributed over multi-decade baselines. In GSC, the
key discriminator is the \emph{sign} of the effect at high redshift,
which reduces the dependence on absolute model fits and emphasizes
systematic control. \# 9. What Was Removed from v9.1 and Why (v10 Change
Log Summary)

v10 is not ``v9.1 plus more ideas.'' It is a pruning and
renormalization.

\textbf{Removed from main claims:}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  ADD / large extra dimensions and any large exponent (\(n\approx 36\)):
  this is curve-fitting.
\item
  Casimir ``10--100 nm deviations'' prediction: high risk of existing
  falsification; removed.
\item
  Cosmic-background torsion explanation of neutron lifetime: fails by
  many orders of magnitude; removed.
\item
  Claims of solving Li-7: removed unless a full deuterium-consistent
  calculation exists.
\item
  Overextended thermodynamic/information narratives that produced
  internal contradictions: reduced to speculative discussion only.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Kept and strengthened:}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  Freeze-frame / conformal-duality interpretation as a viable frame (via
  Wetterich-style transformations).
\item
  RG-flow mechanism as the only gravity enhancement.
\item
  Scale covariance as the reason local tests show null drift.
\item
  Redshift drift as the decisive discriminant.
\end{itemize}

\begin{center}\rule{0.5\linewidth}{0.5pt}\end{center}

\hypertarget{open-problems-and-v10-roadmap}{%
\section{10. Open Problems and v10+
Roadmap}\label{open-problems-and-v10-roadmap}}

v10 is intentionally conservative. The following are required for a v10+
``full theory'':

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
\item
  \textbf{Derive \(k_*\) (or \(\ell_*\)) from first principles}\\
  Connect the critical RG scale to a hadronic/confinement scale and/or
  to a controlled FRG truncation. Make explicit and testable the map
  between RG scale and cosmological/structural scale (e.g.
  \(k\leftrightarrow 1/\sigma\) or related constructions).
\item
  \textbf{Construct a consistent scalar-tensor action with universal
  scaling}\\
  Show explicitly how hadronic and electroweak scales co-scale without
  violating WEP bounds.
\item
  \textbf{Structure formation and dark sector phenomenology}\\
  Determine whether additional fields/defects are required, or whether
  the collapse framework can reproduce DM/DE phenomenology in
  perturbations.
\item
  \textbf{Local microphysics modules (torsion, nuclear physics)}\\
  Any neutron/BBN claims must be rebuilt on a local intrinsic mechanism
  and confronted with existing laboratory bounds, not with optimistic
  summaries.
\end{enumerate}

\hypertarget{early-timecmb-closure-checkpoint-diagnostic-only}{%
\subsection{10.1 Early-time/CMB closure checkpoint
(diagnostic-only)}\label{early-timecmb-closure-checkpoint-diagnostic-only}}

The v11.0.0 canonical release is late-time only. However, strict
compressed CMB distance priors (CHW2018: \(R\), \(\ell_A\),
\(\omega_b h^2\) + published covariance) provide a high-leverage
reviewer check on what an early-time closure would need to change. The
table below records diagnostic-only numbers for a representative
non-degenerate bridge checkpoint.

\textbf{Localized failure (diagnostic-only):} in this checkpoint, the
distance-budget diagnostic shows that the excess in \(D_M(z_*)\) is
dominated by the integral contribution from \(z\in[2,5]\); for
\(z>z_{\rm used}\) the bridge enforces \(\Delta D_M\simeq 0\) by
construction.

\begin{table}[htbp]
\centering
\small
\setlength{\tabcolsep}{4pt}
\renewcommand{\arraystretch}{1.15}
\begin{tabular}{@{}p{0.40\linewidth} p{0.18\linewidth} p{0.36\linewidth}@{}}
\textbf{Diagnostic} & \textbf{Value} & \textbf{Note} \\
\hline
Distance-budget excess in \(D_M(z_*)\) (E1.3) & \(\Delta D_M[2,5]\approx +1070~{\rm Mpc}\) & For \texttt{gsc\_transition} (\(p=0.6\), \(z_{\rm transition}=1.8\)) at non-degenerate bridge \(z_{\rm used}=5\): the excess is dominated by \(2<z<5\); for \(z>5\) the bridge enforces \(\Delta D_M\simeq 0\) by construction. \\
Joint-fit closure knobs (E2.2) & \(dm_*\approx 0.92909\), \(rs_*\approx 1.0045\) & Multipliers on \(D_M(z_*)\) and \(r_s(z_*)\) in the CHW2018 compressed-priors distance-priors prediction path (diagnostic-only). Here \(dm_*\approx 0.92909\) corresponds to about \(-7.1\%\) in \(D_M(z_*)\). \\
Strict CHW2018 \(\chi^2\) after joint fit (E2.2) & \(\chi^2_{\rm cmb,min}\approx 0.0177\) (ndof \(=3\)) & Confirms that distance closure (via \(R\propto D_M\)) is required; \(r_s(z_*)\) rescaling alone cannot repair \(R\). \\
\end{tabular}
\caption{Diagnostic-only early-time closure numbers under strict CHW2018
